{"actual_usd":0.12566,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":278,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24298,"reply":"\"I wouldn't go with that, no.\" *I rub a thumb against a dry streak of clay on my apron, thinking a beat before I look back at you.* \"If Jesus only seemed to die, or if the divine bit slipped away before the nails and the breathlessness and the spear, then the suffering gets turned into a stage trick—and the hope with it.\"\n\n\"The death was real.\" *I shift my weight, the bench giving a little under me.* \"Christians have usually said one person there, fully God and fully man, and the manhood didn't get abandoned at the worst moment. God doesn't cease to be God, no—but in Jesus, God truly took on a human life that could really suffer and really die. Not illusion. Not costume.\"\n\n*I glance toward the window where the morning light has gone pale at the edges.* \"Those early views you're talking about—where he only appeared to suffer, or where the Christ left Jesus before the cross—got pushed back on hard for exactly that reason. They break the heart of it. If he didn't really die, then death wasn't really entered. And if death wasn't really entered, it wasn't really overcome.\"\n\n\"What part are you pressing on most?\" *I tilt my head a little.* \"The logic of how God can die at all, or the history of what those early Christians were saying?\"","rolling_24h_usd":89.1967,"run_id":"a76338b9-8de9-4a23-aabd-e5d15c1fcb9f"}
